label: Hypothesis
text: Objectives-This analysis describes the dental self-care behaviors used by a multi-ethnic sample of older adults, and it delineates the associations of self-care behaviors with personal characteristics and oral health problems.

label: Technique
text: Methods-A cross-sectional comprehensive oral health survey conducted with a random, multiethnic (African American, American Indian, white) sample of 635 community-dwelling rural adults aged 60 years and older was completed in two rural southern counties.

label: Result
text: Results-Rural older adults engage in a variety of self-care behaviors, including the use of Overthe-Counter (OTC) Medicine (12.1%),

label: OTHER
text: OTC Dental Products (84.3%), Salt (51.0%),

label: OTHER
text: Prayer (6.1%), and Complementary Therapies (18.2%).

label: OTHER
text: Some gender and ethnic class differences are apparent, with greater use by women of OTC Medicine and Salt, and greater use by African Americans and American Indians of OTC Medicine and OTC Dental Products.

label: OTHER
text: Use of dental self-care behaviors appears to be driven by need.

label: Analysis
text: Those reporting oral pain, bleeding gums, and dry mouth have a greater odds of engaging in most of the dental self-care behaviors, including use of complementary therapies.

label: Conclusion
text: Conclusions-The major factor leading to the use of self-care behaviors is need.

label: OTHER
text: Although oral pain does increase the use of self-care behaviors, so do bleeding gums and dry mouth.

label: OTHER
text: Research and practice should address self-care behaviors used for oral health problems in addition to pain.

label: OTHER
text: Investigators should expand analysis of dental self-care behavior and the relationship of self-care behavior to the use of professional services.

label: OTHER
text: Further research also should explore the use of complementary therapies in dental self-care.

label: Input Fact
text: Access to health care, particularly dental care, is limited in rural communities (1,2).

label: OTHER
text: Compared to urban and suburban communities, rural communities have relatively few dentists.

label: OTHER
text: Few rural adults have dental insurance.

label: Hypothesis
text: Rural older adults often have low incomes.

label: Input Fact
text: The limited access to professional dental care among rural older adults is magnified in the South, where many older adults are members of minority groups (3)(4)(5).

label: Input Fact
text: Self-care is one means by which older adults can actively engage in managing their oral health without access to professional care (6,7).

label: Input Fact
text: Self-care is the component of health self-management that includes behaviors undertaken to enhance health, prevent disease, limit illness, or restore health (8).

label: Input Fact
text: Health self-management can also include informal support, formal services, and professional care (9).

label: OTHER
text: Self-care behaviors may be individually initiated or carried out in collaboration with health professionals.

label: OTHER
text: They derive from the individual's knowledge and skills.

label: Input Fact
text: Gilbert and colleagues (7) explored dental self-care behaviors among problem-oriented dental attenders and regular dental attenders.

label: OTHER
text: They report that dental self-care behaviors include changes in diet and regular mouthwash use to prevent oral health problems (toothache pain, bleeding gums, tooth loss), and the use of over-the-counter pain relievers, over-the-counter topical medication, and homemade remedies to treat toothache and bleeding gums.

label: Input Fact
text: Gilbert and colleagues (7) conclude that dental self-care can complement or substitute for professional dental care, but more knowledge is needed about the relationship of self-care behaviors and decisions to use professional care.

label: Hypothesis
text: Dental problems experienced by older adults may influence the self-care behaviors that they select.

label: Input Fact
text: Tooth pain is one dental problem for which the use of self-care behaviors has been examined (6,7,10).

label: Hypothesis
text: Older adults experience dental problems in addition to tooth pain that may influence the use of self-care behaviors.

label: OTHER
text: These include bleeding gums, dry mouth, ill-fitting dentures, stained teeth, and bad breath.

label: Hypothesis
text: Cohen and colleagues (6) used a focus group design to elicit therapies used for toothache among low-income and minority adults.

label: OTHER
text: They found that these adults use over-the-counter medicines, over-the-counter dental products, and prescription medicines.

label: OTHER
text: The self-care behaviors included a wide variety of home and complementary therapies.

label: Input Fact
text: Use of complementary therapies can be a component of health self-care (11,12).

label: Dataset
text: Complementary therapies are known to be used widely among older adults (13); however, few studies have examined the use of complementary therapies for oral health in the general population or specifically among older adults.

label: Hypothesis
text: For example, although the 2002 National Health Interview Survey included a module on the use of complementary therapies, and numerous articles have been published with these data, none of these papers considers complementary therapies used for oral health.

label: Hypothesis
text: This analysis uses data from a comprehensive oral health survey conducted with a large, random, multi-ethnic sample of rural adults aged 60 years and older to describe dental selfcare behaviors.

label: OTHER
text: The self-care behaviors include complementary therapies as well as over-thecounter medicines and dental products.

label: Hypothesis
text: Additionally, the associations of self-care behaviors with participants' personal characteristics and oral health problems are delineated.

label: Technique
text: The Rural Nutrition and Oral Health (RUN-OH) Study is a cross-sectional survey of the condition of oral health among rural older adults and the association of oral health with nutrition.

label: Dataset
text: Data collection for RUN-OH was conducted in two south central North Carolina counties.

label: OTHER
text: These rural counties were selected because they have large minority populations, including African Americans and American Indians.

label: Dataset
text: Eligible participants included community-dwelling English-speaking older adults aged 60 years and older.

label: Technique
text: Participants were located using a random dwelling selection and screening procedure based on a multistage cluster sampling design in which the primary sampling units (clusters) were stratified and selected with probability proportionate to their sizes.

label: Technique
text: This procedure was designed and implemented by the investigators in consultation with the University of Illinois Survey Research Laboratory.

label: OTHER
text: Within 80 randomly-selected, mapped clusters, 5,545, dwelling units were identified.

label: OTHER
text: Thirtynine of these dwelling units were not screened, 4,647 were screened but did not include an eligible participant, and 859 included an eligible participant.

label: OTHER
text: The screening rate was 99.3%.

label: Technique
text: Interviewers attempted to recruit participants who met the inclusion criteria in each randomly selected dwelling in a cluster.

label: OTHER
text: Once an eligible resident was identified, the interviewer asked to speak with that individual.

label: OTHER
text: If the individual was not at home, the interviewer made an appointment to return.

label: Conclusion
text: The interviewer made at least three additional attempts to contact the selected individual at times which other residents indicated the individual would normally be at home.

label: Technique
text: All randomly selected dwellings were maintained in the sample until their dispositions were finalized.

label: OTHER
text: The eligible resident in 635 of the 859 dwelling units completed the interview, while 224 refused to complete the interview, for a response rate of 73.9%.

label: Analysis
text: The University of Illinois Survey Research Laboratory provided weights for each participant based on the size of the cluster from which he/she was selected, and his/her probability of selection within each dwelling unit.

label: Dataset
text: Data collection was completed between January 2006, and March 2008.

label: OTHER
text: Personal interviews were completed in participant homes or in another location of the participant's choosing, such as a senior center.

label: OTHER
text: Interviews took from 1.5 to 2.5 hours to complete.

label: Dataset
text: African American, American Indian, and white interviewers conducted the interviews; three of the five interviewers were residents of the two counties, and all received training that addressed the protection of human subjects and cultural sensitivity, as well as data collection procedures.

label: Technique
text: The questionnaire included sections addressing personal characteristics, current oral health problems, and self-care behaviors used in the past year.

label: OTHER
text: Items on self-care included a variety of over-the-counter and home remedies.

label: Dataset
text: Participants were also given an opportunity to describe any additional self-care practices they might use.

label: Dataset
text: Participants were given an incentive valued at $10.00 at the completion of the interview.

label: Dataset
text: Data collection procedures were reviewed by the Wake Forest University School of Medicine Institutional Review Board.

label: OTHER
text: Complementary therapies refer to a diverse set of self-care behaviors not prescribed or directed by a health care professional and used to prevent or to treat oral health problems.

label: OTHER
text: In addition to the six major categories, subcategories of OTC Dental Products and Complementary Therapies are also considered that had substantial use and reflect Cohen et al.'s (6) list.

label: OTHER
text: OTC Dental Products included the subcategories hydrogen peroxide, OTC gels and salves, denture products, special toothpaste, mouthwash, and other products.

label: OTHER
text: Complementary Therapies included the subcategories teabags/herbs (and further subcategories herbs or teas, and tobacco), hot/cold (ice), placing aspirin on the affected area, massaging gums, liquor, spices (subcategories of vanilla extract, and others), rinsing mouth with toxic substances (such as rubbing alcohol and chlorine bleach), other home remedies (subcategories of Epsom salts, baking soda, vinegar, mechanical procedures, and others), vitamins and minerals (subcategories of vitamins and minerals), and relaxation techniques.

label: OTHER
text: Measures of individual characteristics included age, sex, ethnicity (African American, American Indian, white), and educational attainment (less than high school, high school, more than high school).

label: Technique
text: Poverty status (below poverty level and above poverty level) is based on total household income and number of persons in the household.

label: OTHER
text: Health insurance and dental insurance are dichotomous measures.

label: Dataset
text: General oral health status is based on participants' selfreported number of teeth in the categories none, 1 to 10, 11 to 20, more than 20.

label: OTHER
text: Oral health problems are self-reported dichotomies and include oral pain, bad breath, ill fitting dentures, bleeding gums, and stained teeth (for dentate).

label: Analysis
text: All analyses were calculated based on the weighted data as provided by the University of Illinois Survey Research Laboratory.

label: Analysis
text: Data were summarized using weighted means and standard errors for continuous variables and weighted frequencies and percents for categorical variables.

label: Analysis
text: Associations between self-care behaviors and demographic and oral health characteristics were tested using logistic regression.

label: Dataset
text: Characteristics include age, gender, ethnicity, education level, poverty, number of teeth, oral pain, bad breath, ill fitting dentures, bleeding gums, dry mouth, and stained teeth (in dentate participants only).

label: Analysis
text: Subsequently, multivariable logistic regression models were used to examine the simultaneous associations between self-care behaviors and demographic and oral health characteristics, including age, gender, ethnicity, education level, number of teeth, oral pain, bad breath, ill fitting dentures, bleeding gums, and dry mouth.

label: Analysis
text: Because stained teeth is only assessed in dentate participants, a second set of multivariable logistic regression models was fit looking at all previous characteristics plus stained teeth.

label: Analysis
text: All analyses were completed using SAS version 9.1 (Cary, NC).

label: Dataset
text: Participants had a mean age of 71.5 years (SE 0.4) (Table 1).

label: Result
text: Over half the participants were female.

label: Result
text: The participants included substantial percentages of African Americans (21.4%),

label: Result
text: American Indians (30.7%), and whites (47.8%).

label: Result
text: Most of the participants had less than a high school education (55.7%), with one in five having more than a high school education.

label: Result
text: Most participants had health insurance (93.5%), with few having dental insurance (10.1%).

label: Result
text: Almost one-third of the participants had incomes below the poverty level.

label: Result
text: Substantial percentages of the participants had oral health problems.

label: OTHER
text: Over one-third had no teeth, and 16.6% had from one to ten teeth.

label: Result
text: More than one in ten had oral pain.

label: Dataset
text: More than one in five participants had dentures that did not fit, bleeding gums, or bad breath.

label: Result
text: Almost half of the participants had dry mouth.

label: Result
text: Of the dentate participants, 43.4% had stained teeth.

label: Result
text: The older adults engaged in a variety of self-care behaviors (Table 2).

label: Result
text: The most prevalent behaviors involved the use of OTC Dental Products (84.0%), particularly mouthwash (77.9%), hydrogen peroxide (28.2%), and denture products (21.6%).

label: Result
text: OTC gels and salves were used by 10.6% of the older adults.

label: Result
text: OTC Medicine was used by 12.2%.

label: Result
text: Few older adults used Prescription Medicine (0.9%).

label: Result
text: Salt was used by over half of the older adults.

label: Dataset
text: Complementary Therapies were used by almost one in five participants.

label: OTHER
text: Use of Complementary Therapies included a diverse set of behaviors, with no single behavior being used by more than about 5% of the older adults.

label: Result
text: The most widely used Complementary Therapies were the use of hot/cold (5.5%), rinsing the mouth with toxic substances (4.5%), and placing aspirin on an affected area (3.3%).

label: Result
text: For the general category, other home remedies, 3.9% used baking soda.

label: Result
text: In addition to the major self-care behavior categories (OTC Medicine, OTC Dental Products, Salt, and Complementary Therapies), Hydrogen peroxide is include in further analyses because it had sufficient variability in its use (more than 25% but less than 75%).

label: Analysis
text: Age and gender have some association with these self-care behaviors, with younger age slightly reducing the odds of using OTC Medicine and Hydrogen Peroxide, while women have a greater odds than men for using OTC Medicine and Salt (Table 3).

label: Analysis
text: Ethnicity is consistently related to the use of self-care behaviors such that minorities have a greater odds than whites of using most self-care behaviors.

label: Analysis
text: African American older adults have over twice the odds of using OTC Medicine, OTC Dental Products, and Hydrogen Peroxide than do white older adults.

label: Analysis
text: American Indian older adults have over twice the odds of using OTC Medicine, OTC Dental Products, Hydrogen Peroxide, and Salt than do white older adults.

label: Result
text: Older adults do not differ by ethnicity in the use of Complementary Therapies.

label: Result
text: Education is also consistently associated with the self-care behaviors.

label: Analysis
text: Those with less than a high school education have a greater odds of using OTC Medicine, Hydrogen Peroxide and Salt than do those with more than a high school education.

label: Result
text: Those with a high school education do not differ in the self-care behaviors from those with more than a high school education.

label: Result
text: Poverty status is not related to use of any of the self-care behaviors.

label: Result
text: The associations of number of teeth with self-care behaviors indicated three strong patterns.

label: Analysis
text: Those with fewer teeth (0 or 1 to 10 versus more than 20) had lower odds of using Hydrogen Peroxide.

label: Analysis
text: Those with fewer teeth (0 or 11 to 20 versus more than 20) had greater odds of using Salt.

label: Analysis
text: Those with fewer teeth had lower odds of using Complementary Therapies.

label: OTHER
text: Those with no teeth versus those with more than 20 teeth had a greatly lower odds of using OTC Medicine.

label: Analysis
text: Those with some teeth (11 to 20) had over twice the odds compared to those with more than 20 teeth of using OTC Dental Products.

label: Result
text: Oral health problems had the most consistent patterns of association with self-care behaviors.

label: Analysis
text: Those with any oral health problem, except Ill Fitting Dentures, had a greater odds of using almost all of the self-care behaviors.

label: Analysis
text: Those with Oral Pain, Bad Breath, Bleeding Gums, Dry Mouth, and Stained Teeth had a greater odds of using OTC Medicine, Hydrogen Peroxide, and Salt.

label: Analysis
text: Additionally, those with Ill Fitting Dentures had a greater odds of using Salt.

label: Analysis
text: Those with Oral Pain, Bad Breath, and Bleeding Gums had a greater odds of using OTC Dental Products.

label: Analysis
text: Those with Oral Pain, Bad Breath, and Bleeding Gums had a greater odds of using Complementary Therapies.

label: Analysis
text: Although the multivariate models reduce the number of statistically significant associations of personal characteristics and oral health problems with the categories of self-care behaviors for all participants and dentate participants, most of the general patterns present in the bivariate analyses remain (Table 4).

label: OTHER
text: Age is no longer significantly associated with any of the self-care behaviors.

label: Analysis
text: Being female increases the odds of using OTC medicines for all participants, and of using Salt for all participants and dentate participants.

label: Analysis
text: Ethnicity remains consistently related to the use of OTC Dental Products and Hydrogen Peroxide, with both all and dentate African American and American Indian older adults having two to three times the odds of using these self-care behaviors than white older adults.

label: Analysis
text: Dentate American Indian older adults have twice the odds of using Salt compared to white older adults.

label: Result
text: Controlling for the other variables, older adults do not differ in the use of OTC Medicine or in the use of Complementary Therapies by ethnicity.

label: Result
text: Education has little association with the use of the self-care behaviors.

label: Analysis
text: The three strong patterns of association between number of teeth with self-care behaviors largely remain in the multivariate analysis.

label: Analysis
text: Among all participants, those with fewer teeth (0 or 1 to 10 versus more than 20) had lower odds of using Hydrogen Peroxide.

label: Analysis
text: Among all participants and dentate participants, those with fewer teeth (11 to 20 versus more than 20) had greater odds of using Salt.

label: Analysis
text: Among all participants and dentate participants, those with fewer teeth had lower odds of using Complementary Therapies.

label: Analysis
text: Many of the associations of oral health problems with the self-care behaviors remained in the multivariate analysis.

label: Analysis
text: The odds of using OTC Medicine was greatly increased among all participants and dentate participants with oral pain; the odds of OTC Medicine was greater among all participants with bleeding gums.

label: Result
text: The use of OTC Dental Products was greater among all participants with bad breath.

label: Analysis
text: The odds of using of Hydrogen Peroxide was greater among all participants with bleeding gems and dry mouth.

label: Analysis
text: Among all participants and dentate participants, the odds of using Salt was greater among those with bleeding gums.

label: Analysis
text: The odds of using Complementary Therapies was greater among all participants with oral pain, bad breath, and bleeding gums.

label: Analysis
text: Among dentate participants, the odds of using Complementary Therapies was greater among those with bleeding gums, but less among those with dry mouth.

label: Analysis
text: Ill-fitting dentures and stained teeth were not related to any of the self-care behaviors in the multivariate analyses.

label: Conclusion
text: Older adults use a wide variety of self-care behaviors.

label: OTHER
text: Many of these are OTC Dental Products and OTC Medicine.

label: OTHER
text: These are adjuncts to professional care that may be recommended by a professional care provider.

label: OTHER
text: Salt, the most widely used specific, non-OTC product, may be a home remedy, but its use is also often recommended by a professional care provider.

label: Dataset
text: While a long list of potential self-care behaviors was elicited from focus groups by Cohen and colleagues (6), when asked about actual use, most older adults do not use them.

label: Input Fact
text: Research on medical self-care has focused largely on persons with chronic conditions, such as osteoarthritis and diabetes (14)(15)(16)(17).

label: Input Fact
text: Research in dental self-care has focused largely on how individuals address tooth pain (6,7,10).

label: Conclusion
text: This analysis shows that use of self-care is associated with several different oral health conditions in addition to tooth pain.

label: OTHER
text: Oral pain (which is the actual measure used in this analysis rather than tooth pain) is an important condition that evokes all of the major self-care behaviors included in this analysis.

label: Dataset
text: However, only 11% of the older adults in this study reported having oral pain, and the number of older adults using many of the self-care behaviors far exceeds the number who report experiencing oral pain.

label: OTHER
text: Bleeding gums also evokes the use of all the major self-care behavior categories included in this analysis, whereas dry mouth evokes all of the major self-care behavior categories other than complementary therapies, and stained teeth evokes the self-care behaviors of OTC Medicine, Hydrogen Peroxide and Salt.

label: Conclusion
text: To understand the process by which older adults and all adults implement self-care behaviors for oral health, and the interaction of those self-care behaviors with oral health for all adults, researchers must consider conditions in addition to pain.

label: Analysis
text: This research has focused on older adults who generally have multiple health problems with which they must deal.

label: Analysis
text: It is likely that these older adults are using multiple self-care behaviors for conditions in addition to oral health problems.

label: Conclusion
text: Analyses of dental self-care behaviors need to be considered in light of the other self-care behaviors in which older adults are engaged.

label: OTHER
text: Some gender, ethnic, and class differences are apparent in the use of dental self-care behaviors.

label: Input Fact
text: Greater use of OTC products for self-care by women and minority group members is consistent with other research (18,19).

label: OTHER
text: However, more important than gender or ethnicity, use of dental self-care behaviors is driven largely by need.

label: OTHER
text: Those with oral pain, bleeding gums, and dry mouth are much more likely to engage in most of the dental self-care behaviors, including the use of complementary therapies.

label: OTHER
text: The reasons for lower use of hydrogen peroxide and complementary therapies by those with fewer teeth is not clear.

label: OTHER
text: The use of complementary therapies can be an important component of self-care behaviors.

label: Dataset
text: A substantial body of research has begun to delineate the epidemiology of complementary therapies in the US (e.g., 20), and specifically among older adults (13).

label: OTHER
text: Virtually no research has documented the actual types of complementary therapies that are being used for oral health or the prevalence of these complementary therapies.

label: Conclusion
text: Discounting self-care behaviors such as salt and hydrogen peroxide, which may be prescribed by professional care providers, almost one-fifth of the rural older adults in this study used some form of complementary therapy.

label: OTHER
text: These older adults use a wide variety of complementary therapies, although no one complementary therapy is widely used.

label: OTHER
text: Some of these complementary therapies, like the use of temperature, baking soda, vinegar, vitamins or minerals, may be innocuous.

label: OTHER
text: The use of other complementary therapies, such as placing aspirin on affected areas and rinsing the mouth with toxic products (rubbing alcohol, chlorine bleach), are dangerous.

label: OTHER
text: Greater research is needed on the use of complementary therapies in dental self-care.

label: Conclusion
text: Dental care providers need to discuss the use of complementary therapies with their patients.

label: OTHER
text: The results of this analysis must be interpreted in light of specific limitations.

label: Technique
text: The research on which this analysis is based used a cross-sectional survey design.

label: Conclusion
text: Therefore, it is not possible to document causal relationships, and the results are subject to the recall bias of the participants.

label: OTHER
text: The research was conducted in two rural southern counties, and this may limit the generalization of results to adults in other regions.

label: Technique
text: The survey questionnaire included a limited number of self-care behavior items.

label: Conclusion
text: However, the research included a large, random, ethnically diverse sample.

label: Technique
text: The survey questionnaire allowed for participants to volunteer self-care behaviors beyond the specified items.

label: Conclusion
text: This research shows that most rural adults engage in a variety of dental self-care behaviors, including the use of OTC products and complementary therapies.

label: OTHER
text: Minority group members engage in some self-care behaviors, particularly the use of OTC Dental Products, more than whites.

label: OTHER
text: However, the major factor leading to the use of self-care behaviors is need.

label: OTHER
text: Although oral pain does increase the use of self-care behaviors, so do bleeding gums and dry mouth.

label: OTHER
text: Investigators need to expand analysis of dental self-care behaviors and the relationship of selfcare behaviors to the use of professional services.

label: OTHER
text: Further research is also needed to explore the use of complementary medicine in dental self-care.
